#Writing Outline

I find these results encouraging. The higher variance in females is visible across a variety of genetic backgrounds, including those in which females have lower means than males.

I feel like this result solidifies a plan for Chapter 3.

It could take the following basic form: Lower stringency of checkpoints during oogenesis predicts higher variance in crossover number within females Despite acceptance of this prediction, it has rarely been tested We tested the prediction across a wide array of genetic backgrounds Females consistently have higher variance than males in the same inbred line, with little evidence for line effects [Perhaps something about variance in SC length] In terms of recombination mechanisms, our results mean In terms of evolutionary mechanisms, our results imply

How much do CO counts vary among cells from the same individual?

What factors shape between-cell variance in CO count?

The approach will use the same glm models as in Chapter 2. A motivation for addressing these questions is that the variance of a quantitative trait can impact the evolution.

Permutations; MLH1

Wed like to know if the set of strains has bigger differences in between-cell variance than expected by chance. Your liner models provide one test, but they could suffer from small sample sizes per mouse. We can conduct a permutation test that enables you to pool all cells in each strain to increase the sample size.

The plots above show the distributions of permuted VAS for 10,000 permutations, the vertical line shows the observed VAS.

The proportion of permutations which are less than the oberserved VAS are 0.46 and 0.83 for male and female respectively

Permutations: var(F) - var(M)

  1. Choose 1 strain.
  2. Compute femaleVar-maleVar (pooling all high-quality cells within sexes for that strain).
  3. Permute cells between sexes.
  4. Compute femaleVar-maleVar for the permuted dataset.
  5. Repeat 3-4 10,000 times.
  6. Compare the observed value to the distribution of permuted values to compute a p-value.
  7. Repeat 1-6 separately for each strain.

Above are the plots for observed sex differences for pooled cell variance. The first plot shows that all female values are higher than male, but PWD and KAZ have the lowest female variance and close to the highest male variance.

The above plots show the difference of Female.var - Male.var for n=10,000 permutations.

For all strains the female cell variance is larger than if cells are randomized across sex. But the degree of the difference varies. PWD and KAZ females have smaller between cell variance.

I should assess how these strain differences might be affected by the number of mice and cells, (espically MOLF).
